Asia
----
[4] Philippines (Western Visayas)
Date: Fri 20 Jul 2012
Source: Sun Star Bacolod [edited]
http://www.sunstar.com.ph/bacolod/local-news/2012/07/20/bacolod-measles-cases-highest-region-233018


Bacolod city has the highest number of measles cases in Western Visayas with the number almost doubling in the 2nd quarter of this year [2012] compared to last year, as reported by the Department of Health (DOH) Assistant Regional Director Dr. Emelia Monicimpo, who was in the city Thursday [19 Jul 2012] to launch the School-based Outbreak Immunization at the Rizal Elementary School to fight the spread of measles among schoolchildren in the city. The program is a joint initiative of the DOH, Department of Education (DepEd) and the City of Bacolod.

"In 2011, Bacolod had 32 cases for the entire year, but in the 2nd quarter of 2012, it has almost doubled, with 51 laboratory confirmed cases," Monicimpo said. Monicimpo said children are susceptible to measles. She lamented that despite the many campaigns of the DOH that started in 1998, many children remain unvaccinated. Bacolod City Schools Superintendent Dr. Gemma Ledesma, who attended the program launching, said they were honored that the anti-measles campaign was launched at Rizal Elementary School. "We will benefit the most from this program. I hope that this strengthens the relations of DepEd, DOH and the city. We are one in saving lives. This program will save the lives of our schoolchildren," she said.

The event was also attended by Mayor Evelio Leonardia, Councilors Sonya Verdeflor and Em Ang, City Health Officer Dr. Salome Binas, Dr. Renilyn P. Reyes, and Rizal Elementary School Principal Mae Bautista also joined Monicimpo.

[Byline: Carla N. Canet]

