The Americas
------------
[5] USA (Arizona)
Date: Thu 19 Jul 2012
Source: Arizona Daily Sun [edited]
http://azdailysun.com/news/local/measles-case-surfaces-in-flagstaff/article_e1b77779-6dcf-50b6-9139-2ccea376fbf3.html


A case of measles has been diagnosed in a Flagstaff, AZ child. The child, who is recovering, was likely contagious from 4 to 12 Jul 2012, according to Coconino County public health officials. The respiratory virus is noteworthy because it is highly contagious and can be spread by coughs and sneezes, lingering in the air for 2 hours after an infected person has left a room. This child spends little time outside the home, so public health officials think the risk to others is low.

Measles is a respiratory illness caused by the rubeola virus. Symptoms include fever, cough, runny nose, red eyes for a few days followed by rash. The rash typically starts on the face and progresses downward and outward, reaching the extremities last. The contagious period usually begins 4 days prior to the onset of rash but can occur even before symptoms start. Complications from measles can range from an ear infection to encephalitis, or death in children in rare cases. Pregnant women who develop measles are more likely to miscarry, deliver prematurely, or have a baby with a very low birth weight.

Vaccination is the most effective means of protection against measles, typically requiring 2 doses for those born after 1957. The measles vaccine is mandatory for children one year and older to attend daycare, preschool or school. Residents are urged to contact a healthcare facility or doctor's office prior to arrival if a measles infection is suspected, especially if a fever has lingered for a few days and a rash is now developing.

