[7] Australia (Queensland)
Date: Mon 16 Jul 2012
Source: 612 ABC Brisbane [edited]
http://www.abc.net.au/local/stories/2012/07/16/3546915.htm


Queensland Health is urging Brisbane residents to be alert for symptoms of the highly infectious measles virus as a case of the potentially deadly disease is confirmed. Rod Davidson, a Queensland Health physician says the person visited Chermside Shopping Centre on Thursday [12 Jul 2012] last week and the Brisbane Domestic airport on Friday [13 Jul 2012] while in the infectious period.

Dr Davidson says people should be cautious if they may have visited the public places. "We have one case, but we are worried that we could have an outbreak." He says the disease is hard to track, and health bodies rely on public awareness when cases are confirmed. "We're currently tracking all known contacts. But when they're in a public arena, we rely on getting the message out to the public and people becoming aware that they may have been in contact. The problem is, measles is a airborne infection, it transmits in small airborne droplets. Those airborne droplets can hang around for up to 2 hours after the person has coughed or sneezed. Initial symptoms include fever, lethargy, runny nose, moist cough and sore and red eyes, followed a few days later by a blotchy red rash. The rash starts on the face then becomes widespread. Many people are in bed for 2 weeks or more, with difficulty looking at the light, fevers, and a significant number of people get middle ear infections and pneumonia."

Dr Davidson says the infectious period begins 4 days before a visible rash. Queensland Health recommends anyone born during or since 1966 who has not had 2 documented doses of measles, mumps, rubella (MMR) vaccine or had proven measles should visit their local GP to get a free vaccine for measles. If you are concerned you may have come into contact with the infected person in Chermside or at the airport, Dr Davidson advises you contact your GP to make an appropriate appointment time to be seen to avoid any potential further spread of the disease. For more information on the measles virus, contact your local GP or call Queensland Health's phone line 13 HEALTH (13 43 25 84).

[Byline: Emma Sykes]

